		<title>By: John Mortensen</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/chords/adding-chords-bass-grooves-riff-week.html#comment-15519</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[John Mortensen]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 29 Nov 2014 04:18:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=7620#comment-15519</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[This one is gold Scott but I have two questions...

I notice when playing along with the backing track that one of the guitar comps does not agree rhythmically with the bass riff at the end of the second bar.  Was this intentional or did the guitarist boof it?

Also, I absolutely love the rhythm of the descending tenth chords at the end of the riff.  But this is something that I would never instinctively play or come up with on my own.  How can one develop a natural feel for creating these types of rhythms?]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This one is gold Scott but I have two questions&#8230;</p>
<p>I notice when playing along with the backing track that one of the guitar comps does not agree rhythmically with the bass riff at the end of the second bar.  Was this intentional or did the guitarist boof it?</p>
<p>Also, I absolutely love the rhythm of the descending tenth chords at the end of the riff.  But this is something that I would never instinctively play or come up with on my own.  How can one develop a natural feel for creating these types of rhythms?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
